      <guid>https://sharief007.github.io/dev-docs/graph-theory/search/breadth-first-search/</guid>
      <description>Breadth-First Search (BFS) is a graph traversal algorithm that explores a graph level by level, starting from a chosen source node. It visits all the immediate neighbors of the source node first, then moves on to their neighbors, and so forth, until it has visited all reachable nodes.
Examples let&amp;rsquo;s consider a few different types of graphs and perform BFS on them.
Graph 1: Undirected Unweighted Graph 0 -- 1 -- 2| | |3 -- 4 5 Traversal Results starting from node 0:</description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Breadth-First Search (BFS) is a graph traversal algorithm that explores a graph level by level, starting from a chosen source node. It visits all the immediate neighbors of the source node first, then moves on to their neighbors, and so forth, until it has visited all reachable nodes.</p>
<h3>Examples<span class="absolute -mt-20" id="examples"></span>
    <a href="#examples" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"></a></h3><p>let&rsquo;s consider a few different types of graphs and perform BFS on them.</p>
<h4>Graph 1: Undirected Unweighted Graph<span class="absolute -mt-20" id="graph-1-undirected-unweighted-graph"></span>
    <a href="#graph-1-undirected-unweighted-graph" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"></a></h4><div class="code-block relative mt-6 first:mt-0 group/code"><pre><code id="code-block-0">   0 -- 1 -- 2
   |    |    |
   3 -- 4    5</code></pre><div class="opacity-0 transition group-hover/code:opacity-100 flex gap-1 absolute m-[11px] right-0 top-0">
    <button class="code-copy-btn group/copybtn transition-all active:opacity-50 bg-primary-700/5 border border-black/5 text-gray-600 hover:text-gray-900 rounded-md p-1.5 dark:bg-primary-300/10 dark:border-white/10 dark:text-gray-400 dark:hover:text-gray-50" title="Copy code" data-clipboard-target="#code-block-0">
