      <description>Depth First Search (DFS) is an algorithm for traversing or searching through a tree or graph data structure. It starts at a chosen node and explores as far as possible along each branch before backtracking. This means it goes as deep as possible down one branch before moving to the next branch.
Examples let&amp;rsquo;s consider a few different types of graphs and perform DFS on them.
Graph 1: Undirected Unweighted Graph 0 -- 1 -- 2| | |3 -- 4 5 Traversal Results starting from node 0:</description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Depth First Search (DFS) is an algorithm for traversing or searching through a tree or graph data structure. It starts at a chosen node and explores as far as possible along each branch before backtracking. This means it goes as deep as possible down one branch before moving to the next branch.</p>
<h3>Examples<span class="absolute -mt-20" id="examples"></span>
